<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/F5kwsbcWG5k&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/F5kwsbcWG5k&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>One Night in Bangkok / Murray Head</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">This was played to death on the radio at the end of 1985 - tremendously catchy, and you can hear the ABBA influence. <b><i>(3:55)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F5kwsbcWG5k" target="F5kwsbcWG5k">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
Amusingly, I also tinkered about with <i>VU-3D</i>, a simple CAD program
which had a ray-tracing feature. "Little did I know... " that around
twenty years later I'd be using a 3D animation package I wrote which
used a ray-tracer as a renderer!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As I was currently addicted to those 1982- and 1983-era titles, I
don't know what I would have made of 1985's offerings. From a
historian's perspective, it was this Christmas which featured coin-op
conversions entering the festive charts. Indeed, the #1 and #2 games
(<i>Commando</i> and <i>Yie Ar Kung Fu</i>) came from the arcades, and it was
<i>Commando</i> which was exciting the press at the time.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I say "exciting", but to put this into perspective this was 1985 -
little hype, and Sinclair User's half-page preview was damning with
faint praise: "The action is chaotic and the animation smooth.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/2yoEVJXxQE0&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/2yoEVJXxQE0&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas Adverts from 1985</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A nice selection of ads from 1985 - you don't get many cartoon-style of adverts these days. My father filled a cupboard with those free petrol station glasses... <b><i>(3:44)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2yoEVJXxQE0" target="2yoEVJXxQE0">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<i>Commando</i> is very similar to the original, but in terms of the
Spectrum's graphics, colour and sound, it can't compete." I guess the
author was still getting used to the idea of coin-op conversions where
the arcade hardware had moved on a generation! Your Sinclair were far
more enthusiastic in their launch issue's MegaPreview.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d10_1985_ad2.png" target="1985_ad2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d10_1985_ad2_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=142></a></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
The final reviews were definitely more appreciable, though, with top
marks across the board. Just as well considering it became the
Christmas #1! It didn't age too well, though - this was the first
fast, furious and fun "<i>Commando</i>-type game" that was released, and once
the novelty wore off and other software houses had their stabs at the
genre, by the time <i>Commando</i> got re-released in 1989 the YS reviewer
only gave it a six, ending the review with "I'd say you're better off
going for a <i>Commando</i>-type game than <i>Commando</i> itself. Amazing but
true."
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
